As we pass with him into the under world, by the sole force of genius he makes a dream seem to us a living fact-3 he corn- mands our thoughts to follow whithersoever he leads them, and they obey3 under his guidance we tread with ghostly but unhesitating footsteps that dim and unknown highway which extends beyond the grave.

For an ordinary man, however, to criticise Virgil is almost an impertinence. It needs a poet to appreciate a poet, and the judgment of Alfred Tennyson outweighs that of a host of critics and commentators.
